**File:** `src/components/Button/Button.tsx`

```tsx
import React from 'react';
import './Button.css';

export interface ButtonProps {
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'ghost';
  size?: 'sm' | 'md' | 'lg';
  disabled?: boolean;
  onClick?: () => void;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

export type ButtonVariant = 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'ghost';
export type ButtonSize = 'sm' | 'md' | 'lg';

export const Button = ({
  children,
  variant = 'primary',
  size = 'medium',
  disabled = false,
  onClick,
  ...props
}: ButtonProps) => {
  return (
    <button
      className={`btn btn-${variant} btn-${size}`}
      disabled={disabled}
      onClick={onClick}
      {...props}
    >
      {children}
    </button>
  );
};
```

**Button Component Structure:**

| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|------|------|---------|-------------|
| `variant` | `'primary' \| 'secondary' \| 'ghost'` | `'primary'` | Button style variant |
| `size` | `'sm' \| 'md' \| 'lg'` | `'medium'` | Button size |
| `disabled` | `boolean` | `false` | Whether the button is disabled |
| `onClick` | `() => void` | - | Click handler function |
| `children` | `React.ReactNode` | - | Button content (required) |

**Additional files in the Button folder:**
- `Button.module.css` - Styles for the component
- `index.ts` - Export file
- `types.ts` - Additional type definitions
- `utils.ts` - Utility functions

The component uses a simple CSS class approach with `btn btn-{variant} btn-{size}` for styling. Would you like me to show you the CSS styles or any other component?

Here's the Input component code:

**File:** `src/components/Input/Input.types.ts`

```tsx
import { InputHTMLAttributes, ReactNode } from 'react';

export interface InputProps extends InputHTMLAttributes<HTMLInputElement> {
  /**
   * The variant of the input
   */
  variant?: 'default' | 'filled' | 'outline';
  /**
   * The size of the input
   */
  size?: 'sm' | 'md' | 'lg';
  /**
   * Whether the input is disabled
   */
  disabled?: boolean;
  /**
   * Error message to display
   */
  error?: string;
  /**
   * Left icon element
   */
  leftIcon?: ReactNode;
  /**
   * Right icon element
   */
  rightIcon?: ReactNode;
  /**
   * Callback when input changes
   */
  onChange?: (value: string) => void;
}
```

**Input Component Structure:**

| Prop | Type | Description |
|------|------|-------------|
| `variant` | `'default' \| 'filled' \| 'outline'` | Input style variant |
| `size` | `'sm' \| 'md' \| 'lg'` | Input size |
| `disabled` | `boolean` | Whether the input is disabled |
| `error` | `string` | Error message to display |
| `leftIcon` | `ReactNode` | Icon to display on the left |
| `rightIcon` | `ReactNode` | Icon to display on the right |
| `onChange` | `(value: string) => void` | Callback when input changes |
| *(inherited)* | `InputHTMLAttributes<HTMLInputElement>` | All standard HTML input props (value, placeholder, type, etc.) |

**Comparison with Button:**

| Aspect | Button | Input |
|--------|--------|-------|
| Props interface | Defined inline in component | In separate `Input.types.ts` file |
| Extends | None | `InputHTMLAttributes<HTMLInputElement>` |
| Size options | `'sm' \| 'md' \| 'lg'` | `'sm' \| 'md' \| 'lg'` |
| Variants | `'primary' \| 'secondary' \| 'ghost'` | `'default' \| 'filled' \| 'outline'` |
| Forward ref | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| Extra features | - | Icons (left/right), error messages |

The Input component is more feature-rich than Button - it supports icons on both sides, error states, and extends all standard HTML input attributes. Would you like to see any other components or compare them further?

Here's the Modal component code:

**File:** `src/components/Modal/Modal.tsx`

```tsx
export const Modal = ({
  isOpen,
  onClose,
  children,
  title,
  size = 'medium',
}: ModalProps) => {
  if (!isOpen) return null;

  return (
    <div className="modal-overlay">
      <div className={`modal-content modal-${size}`}>
        <button onClick={onClose} className="modal-close">
          ×
        </button>
        {title && <h2>{title}</h2>}
        {children}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export interface ModalProps {
  /**
   * Whether the modal is visible
   */
  isOpen: boolean;
  onClose: () => void;
  children?: React.ReactNode;
}
```

The Modal also has sub-components:

- `ModalHeader.tsx`
- `ModalBody.tsx`  
- `ModalFooter.tsx`

**Modal Component Structure:**

| Prop | Type | Description |
|------|------|-------------|
| `isOpen` | `boolean` | **Required.** Whether the modal is visible |
| `onClose` | `() => void` | **Required.** Callback when modal is closed |
| `children` | `React.ReactNode` | Modal content |
| `title` | `string` | Optional title displayed at top |
| `size` | `'sm' \| 'md' \| 'lg' \| 'full'` | Modal size (default: `'medium'`) |

**Key differences from Button and Input:**

| Aspect | Button | Input | Modal |
|--------|--------|-------|-------|
| Has state | ❌ No (controlled via props) | ❌ No | ✅ Yes (controls visibility with `isOpen`) |
| Children | ✅ Yes (`children: React.ReactNode`) | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| Conditional rendering | No | No | ✅ Yes (`if (!isOpen) return null`) |
| Sub-components | ❌ No | ❌ No | ✅ Yes (Header, Body, Footer) |
| Controlled | Partially | Fully | Fully |

The Modal is notably more complex - it handles conditional rendering (showing/hiding based on `isOpen`), accepts children for content, includes a close button, and has related sub-components for structured content. Would you like me to show one of the Modal sub-components or any other part of the codebase?

